<i>That God would forgive them.</i>

07:25.711 --> 07:27.156
- Bertie.
- Tony.

07:27.180 --> 07:29.182
- Come through.
Did you have a good journey?

07:29.215 --> 07:31.195
- I did, yes. We came up...

08:35.748 --> 08:37.250
- Divide and conquer.

08:37.283 --> 08:39.229
- Divide and rule.

08:51.230 --> 08:55.178
- To trust them, to acknowledge
their political mandate?

08:55.201 --> 08:57.181
I mean, how can you have
a discussion with someone

08:57.203 --> 08:59.205
who might murder you
if you don't agree with them?

09:03.609 --> 09:05.282
- Policing,
then we're nearly there,

09:05.311 --> 09:07.431
but with the marching,
we're gonna have to fudge that.

09:07.547 --> 09:09.584
Make a new body.
Buy us some time.

09:09.615 --> 09:10.855
Yes? Oh, right.

09:11.717 --> 09:13.219
Just wait a minute.
I'll be back.

09:15.988 --> 09:17.626
- If we're going
with your police,

09:17.657 --> 09:20.297
and that's revolutionary,

09:20.326 --> 09:22.272
and you don't give ground
on parades?

09:34.206 --> 09:35.981
Is there a problem?

09:36.008 --> 09:37.988
- You know
it's his big night tonight.

09:38.010 --> 09:39.011
They've guests coming in

09:39.045 --> 09:40.683
from all over the world
for the celebrations.

09:40.713 --> 09:43.125
- Well, we agreed
it would be fine.

09:43.149 --> 09:45.186
- The storm has closed
Glasgow Airport.

09:45.217 --> 09:47.163
- Ah.

09:47.186 --> 09:48.790
- He'll be devastated.

09:49.855 --> 09:51.300
Is there anything you can do?

09:53.726 --> 09:55.137
- We need a clear
commitment from...

09:55.161 --> 09:56.902
- Hello.

09:56.929 --> 09:59.034
Hi. Hello.

09:59.065 --> 10:02.842
Uh, Gerry, Martin,
bit of a situation.

10:02.868 --> 10:05.644
Um, as you know,

10:05.671 --> 10:07.150
Dr. Paisley is due to attend

10:07.173 --> 10:09.084
his golden wedding
anniversary celebration

10:09.108 --> 10:11.110
in Belfast this evening.

10:11.143 --> 10:15.649
Unfortunately, the weather
has shut Glasgow Airport.

10:15.681 --> 10:19.185
Now, uh, obviously,
this is very important to him.

10:19.218 --> 10:22.222
- Tony and I both agree
that it'd be a nice gesture

10:22.254 --> 10:25.201
and beneficial to the talks
if we could find a way

10:25.224 --> 10:27.670
to get Dr. Paisley
to his celebrations.

10:27.693 --> 10:29.297
- Now, as it happens,
we may be able

10:29.328 --> 10:31.308
to fly him out
of Edinburgh Airport.

10:31.330 --> 10:33.867
Private business jet, bankers.

10:33.899 --> 10:35.207
We've been able
to pull a few strings

10:35.234 --> 10:36.872
and we can get him on board.

10:36.902 --> 10:39.405
And there's a very small
window of opportunity

10:39.639 --> 10:40.640
before the storm shifts.

10:40.673 --> 10:43.051
However...

10:43.075 --> 10:45.021
Before we propose this,

10:45.044 --> 10:46.921
we need to clear it with you.

10:46.946 --> 10:49.790
You know,
favoritism and all that.

10:51.751 --> 10:53.389
- That's absolutely
not a problem.

10:55.788 --> 10:58.826
- Great. Marvelous.

10:58.858 --> 10:59.859
Thank you.

11:01.127 --> 11:02.902
- As long as I fly with him.

11:06.732 --> 11:07.733
- I'm sorry?

11:07.767 --> 11:10.043
- Well, as you well know...

11:11.103 --> 11:13.379
Our protocols dictate

11:13.406 --> 11:15.750
that senior figures
in opposing parties

11:15.775 --> 11:17.015
must fly together.

11:18.110 --> 11:20.454
It lessens the chance
of either side

11:20.680 --> 11:23.126
firing a ground-to-air
missile or...

11:23.149 --> 11:26.824
- Well, surely,
we're beyond the point of...

11:26.852 --> 11:28.195
- Nevertheless.

11:30.256 --> 11:32.031
It would also
give me the opportunity

11:32.058 --> 11:33.731
to consult
with the Army Council.

11:36.362 --> 11:38.364
- Couldn't you just phone them?

11:48.474 --> 11:50.044
- Bertie, we need to talk.

11:58.417 --> 11:59.794
- What are you doing?

12:01.253 --> 12:03.358
- Look, he's going home
into his heartland,

12:03.389 --> 12:04.766
but this time...

12:05.925 --> 12:09.395
If they get a hold of him
before he's said yes,

12:09.428 --> 12:11.339
they will change his mind.

12:11.363 --> 12:13.400
But if Big Ian
doesn't say yes now,

12:13.432 --> 12:15.309
we are just pissing in the wind.

12:17.770 --> 12:19.181
He has to be convinced.

12:19.205 --> 12:20.912
- How?

12:20.940 --> 12:23.750
He hasn't ever spoken
a single word to any of us.

12:23.776 --> 12:24.777
He hates us.

12:24.810 --> 12:27.120
And what if
it's a wild-goose chase?

12:28.080 --> 12:29.957
What if he doesn't speak?

12:29.982 --> 12:33.452
Or what if he does speak
and it all goes to hell?

12:33.486 --> 12:34.897
Martin, we can't take
the risk of-

12:34.920 --> 12:37.230
- We have always
taken the risk, Gerry.

12:38.858 --> 12:40.860
I'd rather it was me and him
going 12 rounds

12:40.893 --> 12:43.999
than that shower of sycophants
that follows him around.

12:45.765 --> 12:47.108
He's 81.

12:48.901 --> 12:51.905
If we don't get to him now,
we will never get to him.

13:00.980 --> 13:02.186
- Don't do this.

13:03.949 --> 13:05.929
Don't cut a deal
with that old bastard.

13:07.887 --> 13:09.867
- I'm not cutting anything,
Rory.

13:11.023 --> 13:12.195
We're just bringing it home.

13:12.224 --> 13:13.999
It's no time for cold feet.

13:16.829 --> 13:19.400
- We announce a ceasefire.
We give up our guns.

13:19.431 --> 13:21.968
We negotiate with the Unionists.

13:22.001 --> 13:23.480
We recognize we're part
of the United Kingdom,

13:23.502 --> 13:25.914
so the Queen is our queen.

13:25.938 --> 13:27.576
We put all
of those things together

13:27.807 --> 13:29.480
and we call it a victory.

13:29.508 --> 13:31.078
Hows that a victory?

13:31.110 --> 13:34.922
- We were fighting for 30 years.
It didn't work.

13:34.947 --> 13:37.553
<i>They could never have beaten us,</i>

13:37.583 --> 13:39.324
<i>but we could never
have beaten them either.</i>

13:39.351 --> 13:41.524
- You should be ashamed
of yourself.

13:41.554 --> 13:42.555
We're soldiers.

13:42.588 --> 13:45.535
<i>There's no shame in losing,
but stand up and admit it.</i>

13:45.558 --> 13:47.902
<i>Don't dress it up
like somehow we've triumphed.</i>

13:49.128 --> 13:51.904
- <i>Politics is</i> a <i>long game, Rory.</i>

13:52.998 --> 13:54.978
<i>You have to stay the course.</i>

13:56.101 --> 13:58.081
<i>Everything we want, we will get.</i>

13:58.103 --> 13:59.446
<i>Maybe not today or tomorrow.</i>

13:59.471 --> 14:01.917
<i>It may take another 30 years.</i>

14:01.941 --> 14:04.945
- Jesus,
I invite you to be with us,

14:04.977 --> 14:07.457
watching over us
and keeping us safe.

14:07.479 --> 14:10.119
- But believe you me,
I would not be talking

14:10.149 --> 14:11.856
to that auld bastard...

14:12.918 --> 14:14.955
If I didn't think
we were gonna get there.

14:14.987 --> 14:17.263
- I pray for an alert mind
whilst traveling.

14:17.289 --> 14:19.394
I pray you keep
this vehicle we're in safe

14:19.425 --> 14:21.098
from mechanical failure.

14:21.126 --> 14:23.970
<i>Thank you for the commitment
you made to me at the cross.</i>

14:23.996 --> 14:25.498
<i>Amen.</i>

14:27.533 --> 14:30.514
- Uh, there's...
well, there's good news

14:30.536 --> 14:32.277
and there's bad news.

14:32.304 --> 14:33.544
- Yes, son?

14:33.572 --> 14:35.882
- Well, the good news is,

14:35.908 --> 14:37.649
they'll get you
to the airport on time.

14:38.544 --> 14:40.490
The bad news...

14:44.617 --> 14:46.426
I'm sorry, Daddy.
We'd no choice.

14:47.987 --> 14:49.967
- It's no skin off my nose.

14:49.989 --> 14:52.469
- You'll be at the airport
in 60 minutes; just say nothing.

14:52.491 --> 14:56.064
- I haven't spoken to him
in 30 years.

14:56.095 --> 14:58.974
Another hour
isn't gonna be any trouble.

15:00.299 --> 15:02.540
- Just enjoy your night.
I wish I could be there.

15:02.568 --> 15:04.377
Don't worry,
I'll hold the fort here.

15:07.606 --> 15:08.914
. Okay

15:13.946 --> 15:16.119
- The jet touches down at 7:00;
the weather's closing in,

15:16.148 --> 15:18.219
so if you're not there,
they won't hang around.

15:18.250 --> 15:20.560
You'll be cleared straight onto
the tarmac, but 7:00, okay?

15:20.586 --> 15:22.566
That's your end game.
- I'll be there by 6:00.

15:47.579 --> 15:49.320
- So far, so good.

16:20.212 --> 16:22.123
- Do I recognize you
from somewhere?

16:22.147 --> 16:23.592
<i>'</i> Hmm?

16:23.615 --> 16:26.323
- I do, don't I?

16:26.352 --> 16:27.763
Are you on TV?

16:27.987 --> 16:30.695
- We're politicians.

16:30.723 --> 16:33.704
- Guess who I had
in the back of the car once.

16:33.726 --> 16:35.706
Samuel L. Jackson.

16:35.728 --> 16:37.605
Oh, I know.
He was playing golf.

16:37.629 --> 16:39.472
Well, not right there
in the back.

16:39.498 --> 16:40.738
At St. Andrews.

16:42.434 --> 16:43.572
Do you follow the golf?

16:45.004 --> 16:48.144
- I'm more of a cricket man
myself, so I am.

16:48.173 --> 16:49.584
- You and me both, pal.

16:51.577 --> 16:54.217
But aren't you, like, Irish
or something?

16:54.246 --> 16:55.966
I just didn't think
the Irish liked cricket.

16:56.015 --> 16:57.426
- There's a lot
would surprise you

16:57.449 --> 16:59.258
about the Irish, so there is.

16:59.284 --> 17:01.059
- And what about you, sir?

17:01.086 --> 17:04.226
- I do not have time
for cricket.

17:04.256 --> 17:07.601
- Ah. Okay, I do know your face.

17:07.626 --> 17:09.263
Who are you really?

17:10.695 --> 17:13.369
- This is Dr. Ian Paisley,

17:13.398 --> 17:16.311
leader of
the Democratic Unionist Party,

17:16.335 --> 17:20.750
founder and moderator
of the Free Presbyterian Church.

17:20.772 --> 17:22.047
- Cool.

17:23.541 --> 17:25.078
And you, sir?

17:25.109 --> 17:27.420
- This is Martin McGuinness,

17:27.445 --> 17:31.622
former chief of staff
of the Irish Republican Army.

17:31.650 --> 17:33.152
- Allegedly.

17:40.359 --> 17:41.770
It's Wild, huh?

17:44.263 --> 17:45.401
The rain.

