with you,

17:49.234 --> 17:51.771
"and all flesh shall
never again be cut off

17:51.804 --> 17:53.715
by the waters of the flood."

17:54.706 --> 17:57.550
- You must have a verse
for every occasion, eh?

17:59.845 --> 18:03.486
How about one
for two auld enemies

18:03.515 --> 18:05.495
in the back of a car,

18:05.517 --> 18:08.225
neither one knowing
how to make the first move?

18:08.253 --> 18:11.530
- I have no interest in moves,

18:11.557 --> 18:12.729
Mr. McGuinness.

18:34.713 --> 18:36.522
- <i>Looks like
the rain's stopping.</i>

18:44.690 --> 18:46.761
You know, I...

18:46.792 --> 18:49.170
I didn't mean to be
disrespectful,

18:49.194 --> 18:50.798
or anything,
not recognizing you.

18:50.829 --> 18:53.469
I just always thought
the IRA was led by that guy

18:53.499 --> 18:55.672
with the beard and the pipe,
you know?

18:57.603 --> 18:59.241
So where do you fit in?

19:01.840 --> 19:05.845
- You might call me
the acceptable public face.

19:12.718 --> 19:14.595
- Forecast is not good.

19:15.621 --> 19:18.693
There will be
a lot of unhappy golfers.

19:19.625 --> 19:21.764
Oh, but then
you're into the old cricket.

19:21.793 --> 19:23.329
- Nicely played.

19:24.530 --> 19:27.443
<i>They should feel free
to speak in front of you.</i>

19:27.466 --> 19:29.639
There's an opportunity here
to see how

19:29.668 --> 19:32.205
<i>they really get on
when no one is watching.</i>

19:32.237 --> 19:35.582
<i>You see, we're hoping
that what they have in common</i>

19:35.607 --> 19:37.678
<i>will be enough
to break down the barriers.</i>

19:39.311 --> 19:41.552
<i>That just the two of them
stripped of all this</i>

19:41.580 --> 19:44.356
<i>bureaucracy and scrutiny</i>

19:44.383 --> 19:46.454
will work this out.

19:46.485 --> 19:50.456
Bring a real and lasting peace.

19:51.423 --> 19:54.404
<i>You're young, aren't you?
25? 26?</i>

19:55.360 --> 19:59.399
<i>Still, old enough that you
should know who these men are.</i>

19:59.431 --> 20:01.741
They are The Troubles.

20:02.768 --> 20:04.645
<i>They are civil war.</i>

20:05.737 --> 20:07.842
They are anarchy.

20:18.817 --> 20:21.229
- I prayed for the bombers
last night.

20:21.253 --> 20:23.358
That God would forgive them.

20:56.588 --> 20:57.623
What?

20:58.490 --> 21:00.902
- Shut his eyes
as soon as he got in.

21:00.926 --> 21:03.600
Been like that
for the last ten minutes.

21:04.696 --> 21:05.970
- Oh, bloody hell.

21:05.998 --> 21:09.468
- He's 81,
and he hasn't been well.

21:09.501 --> 21:10.912
- Thatcher operated
on four hours' sleep

21:10.936 --> 21:11.937
and a pact with the devil.

21:11.970 --> 21:14.610
Paisley has the energy of
ten men half his age.

21:14.640 --> 21:17.348
This is just his way
of not engaging.

21:19.378 --> 21:21.324
Wake him up.
- Hold on.

21:21.346 --> 21:23.053
You know what they say
about sleeping dogs.

21:23.282 --> 21:25.353
- It still needs to be done.

21:25.384 --> 21:27.455
At the end of this,
either we hold the peace

21:27.486 --> 21:28.556
or we go back to war.

21:29.988 --> 21:32.798
You do have a flair
for the dramatic.

21:36.561 --> 21:37.699
- God, sorry!

21:39.831 --> 21:42.311
Oh. I am sorry. Sorry.

21:52.711 --> 21:54.588
- Ay-yi-yi.

22:01.420 --> 22:03.457
So 50 years married, huh?

22:03.488 --> 22:06.799
Oh.
You'd get less time for murder.

22:10.062 --> 22:11.871
I shouldn't have said that.

22:13.065 --> 22:15.807
There's only one possible
comeback...

22:17.069 --> 22:19.709
That I would know
all about murder.

22:21.373 --> 22:22.681
I walked right into it.

22:23.675 --> 22:25.348
Like stepping on a land mine.

22:25.377 --> 22:27.482
Oh, God. There I go again.

22:27.512 --> 22:28.957
- Do you think any of this

22:28.980 --> 22:32.086
is a laughing matter,
Mr. McGuinness?

22:32.117 --> 22:35.496
- No, no, no, absolutely not.

22:38.490 --> 22:40.094
I'm just trying
to break the ice.

22:40.125 --> 22:42.469
- I'm just trying to get home.

22:43.495 --> 22:45.702
- We're all just trying
to get home.

22:48.700 --> 22:50.543
Isn't that profound?

22:59.644 --> 23:00.952
Do you have a signal?

23:06.118 --> 23:09.156
Dr. Paisley, do you have
a mobile phone signal?

23:10.122 --> 23:11.863
- I've absolutely no idea.

23:11.890 --> 23:13.028
- Well, would you check?

23:14.426 --> 23:15.427
- Why?

23:17.796 --> 23:21.608
Do you think I'm gonna lend you
my phone, Mr. McGuinness?

23:21.633 --> 23:24.443
- No, no, of course not.
No, I...

23:24.469 --> 23:25.812
It's just the signal.

23:31.977 --> 23:34.685
So this party of yours
tonight, hmm?

23:34.713 --> 23:36.784
Pints of Guinness
and a bit of boogie, eh?

23:38.617 --> 23:39.618
Oh.

23:39.651 --> 23:40.925
Sorry, I forgot.

23:40.952 --> 23:44.126
Alcohol is the devil's
buttermilk, that right?

23:45.624 --> 23:48.628
And what was it
you said about dancing?

23:48.660 --> 23:51.539
Oh, no, no, no,
not just dancing.

23:51.563 --> 23:53.474
Line dancing.

23:53.498 --> 23:55.500
Poor, inoffensive line dancing.

23:55.534 --> 23:58.538
- Mr. McGuinness,
my party is not your affair.

23:59.604 --> 24:01.982
But for your information,
line dancing is as sinful

24:02.007 --> 24:04.078
as any other type of dancing.

24:04.109 --> 24:06.555
With its sexual gestures
and touching,

24:06.578 --> 24:09.024
it's an incitement to lust.

24:09.047 --> 24:10.720
- Not the way I do it, it isn't.

24:12.617 --> 24:14.028
I'm only winding you up.

24:15.120 --> 24:18.590
- No, Mr. McGuinness,
you're not.

24:29.534 --> 24:33.710
- So what's your position on
the great Samuel L. Jackson,

24:33.738 --> 24:35.081
hmm?

24:35.106 --> 24:37.643
Would you shake his hand
if we stopped to pick him up?

24:39.177 --> 24:43.592
- Andrew Jackson was the seventh
president of the United States.

24:44.683 --> 24:46.890
He was a Presbyterian
of good Ulster stock.

24:46.918 --> 24:48.124
I'd shake his hand.

24:49.221 --> 24:53.260
I've absolutely no idea
who Samuel L. Jackson is.

24:53.492 --> 24:56.029
- Oh. He's a movie star.

24:58.029 --> 25:00.805
<i>Pulp Fiction, Jackie Brown.</i>

25:02.934 --> 25:04.572
<i>Snakes on a Plane.</i>

25:04.603 --> 25:05.707
That's still playing

25:05.737 --> 25:07.216
in the pictures,
if you wanted to go.

25:07.239 --> 25:09.685
- Mr. McGuinness,
I haven't been to the pictures

25:09.708 --> 25:11.915
since 1973.

25:12.978 --> 25:14.048
- Seriously?

25:17.549 --> 25:18.789
Well, what did you go to see?

25:18.817 --> 25:21.161
- I didn't go to see anything.

25:21.186 --> 25:24.065
I was protesting outside.

25:24.089 --> 25:26.831
- 1973...

25:26.858 --> 25:30.032
What would have got your goat
in 1973'?

25:30.061 --> 25:32.735
Uh, 19...

25:32.764 --> 25:36.541
Oh.
Was it The Sting, huh?

25:36.568 --> 25:39.913
All that gambling
offended your sensibilities?

25:40.739 --> 25:41.774
No.

25:43.308 --> 25:45.618
What about you? 1973.

25:45.644 --> 25:47.783
- '73'? Uh...

25:47.812 --> 25:49.883
Hold on.
I'll just phone my granddad.

25:51.716 --> 25:54.754
- Enter the Dragon.
That-that would have been 1973.

25:54.786 --> 25:56.663
Well, too much violence, eh?

25:58.089 --> 25:59.625
No.

25:59.658 --> 26:01.604
No, it wasn't that.

26:01.626 --> 26:04.732
I know what it was. Of course.

26:04.763 --> 26:07.744
<i>The Exorcist. Mm-hmm.</i>

26:09.067 --> 26:11.843
"Your mother sucks"...

26:11.870 --> 26:15.079
- We protested peacefully
outside.

26:15.106 --> 26:17.814
Your lot set incendiary bombs

26:17.842 --> 26:19.719
and burned them down.

26:48.807 --> 26:50.047
Hello, dear.

26:51.343 --> 26:53.345
No, no, everything is fine.

26:55.313 --> 26:57.623
Have our guests
started arriving?

26:59.818 --> 27:02.025
Oh, no, I'll be there on time.

27:03.254 --> 27:05.860
I wouldn't miss it
for the world.

27:08.059 --> 27:10.130
Yes, I have company.

27:12.063 --> 27:15.704
No, no, nobody important.

27:18.203 --> 27:21.184
All right, dear, yes.
Yes, all right, yes.

27:28.313 --> 27:29.986
- So you have a signal.

27:35.286 --> 27:37.926
Could I borrow
your phone, please?

27:37.956 --> 27:39.799
Just-just for
a couple of minutes to-

27:39.824 --> 27:41.735
- No, you may not.

27:41.760 --> 27:44.764
My phone is not
for the likes of you.

27:46.097 --> 27:47.872
- All right, okay.

27:48.967 --> 27:51.811
It's your phone. Absolutely.

27:56.808 --> 27:58.448
Look, if I could
just even send a text to-

27:58.677 --> 27:59.678
- No.

28:01.713 --> 28:04.751
A text is not gonna kill you.

28:04.783 --> 28:09.892
Oh, unless, of course,
it's a-it's an order.

28:11.289 --> 28:12.825
Oh, come on.

28:17.062 --> 28:19.975
Jesus Christ, how are we
supposed to get anything done-

28:19.998 --> 28:22.035
- You watch your language
with me, boy!

28:22.067 --> 28:23.068
- Don't "boy" me!

28:23.101 --> 28:25.047
- Well, do not take
the Lord's name in vain.

28:25.070 --> 28:27.846
- Oh, all right, all right,
okay, okay.

28:35.480 --> 28:37.790
That's always been the problem
with you.

28:39.284 --> 28:41.321
- You have no give in you.
- Really?

28:41.352 --> 28:44.890
That's why we're all
sitting up the road then, is it?

28:44.923 --> 28:45.993
- Just give me the phone,
will you?

28:46.024 --> 28:47.298
Extend the olive branch.

28:47.325 --> 28:49.362
- Well, I'd imagine
you'd be more familiar

28:49.394 --> 28:51.101
with Special Branch.

28:57.335 --> 28:59.042
- That's good.

29:01.506 --> 29:02.917
That's funny.

29:09.214 --> 29:11.888
You've been like this
your whole life, haven't you?

29:14.385 --> 29:16.092
My way or the highway.

29:16.121 --> 29:21.366
- It isn't a question of it
being my way, Mr. McGuinness.

29:21.392 --> 29:24.839
It's a question of it being
the right way, of God's way.

29:24.863 --> 29:27.537
- Oh, because God is always
whispering in your ear.

29:27.766 --> 29:29.768
- Well, perhaps if you
listened a little bit harder,

29:29.801 --> 29:32.441
you might hear him
whispering in your ear too.

29:32.470 --> 29:35.041
- I hear him whispering, okay?
Oh, yeah.

29:36.207 --> 29:38.050
Jesus we pt.

29:42.347 --> 29:45.794
- Are you a married man,
Mr. McGuinness?

29:45.817 --> 29:47.797
- Yes, I am.

29:47.819 --> 29:50.356
- So what does she make
of your, um...

29:51.790 --> 29:53.827
Your career choices?

29:54.492 --> 29:56.369
Of the blood on your hands?

29:56.394 --> 29:59.898
- She's in my corner,
good times and bad.

30:01.099 --> 30:02.237
As I'm sure yours accepts-

30:02.267 --> 30:06.443
- There's no blood on my hands,
Mr. McGuinness.

30:06.471 --> 30:08.348
- Please, stop.

30:09.841 --> 30:11.377
We were at war, never at peace.

30:11.409 --> 30:13.389
- Yes, a peace
that allows your lot

30:13.411 --> 30:16.255
to rob and kill and use that-

30:16.281 --> 30:18.261
- It's not perfect.

30:18.283 --> 30:20.058
But that's why we're here,
isn't it'?

30:20.084 --> 30:21.392
To sort it out.

30:21.419 --> 30:22.955
The final solution.

30:24.355 --> 30:27.393
L-I don't mean
the "final solution."

30:27.425 --> 30:31.134
I mean-
I mean, a final solution.

30:37.368 --> 30:38.403
One way or the other...

30:41.339 --> 30:44.377
I just want to say,
I hope you have a good night.

30:44.409 --> 30:46.286
And a good party.

30:46.311 --> 30:48.257
50 years, hmm.

30:49.547 --> 30:51.925
If you don't mind me asking,

30:51.950 --> 30:57.161
you don't dance,
and you don't drink,

30:57.188 --> 30:58.963
so how did you meet her?

31:05.096 --> 31:06.939
- It was the Titanic.

31:08.600 --> 31:10.011
- How old are you?

31:10.034 --> 31:12.036
- Her father owned
a grocery shop,

31:12.070 --> 31:15.108
bottom of the Nevvtownards Road
right near the shipyard

31:15.139 --> 31:17.983
where the Titanic was built.

31:18.009 --> 31:21.513
I was, uh... I was preaching
on some waste ground opposite.

31:21.546 --> 31:23.150
It was a big crowd.

31:24.148 --> 31:28.153
I could see her standin'
in the shop doorway, apron on,

31:28.186 --> 31:31.463
listening, and my eye
kept coming back to her.

31:31.489 --> 31:35.437
I said, um, "How proud
we should be of the Titanic.

31:35.460 --> 31:37.064
It's such an immense
achievement."

31:37.095 --> 31:40.076
And someone shouted,
"The bloody thing sank!"

31:40.098 --> 31:41.600
And I Said, "Well, it...

31:41.633 --> 31:43.237
it was all right
when it left here."

31:44.636 --> 31:46.946
She was the only one
who laughed.

31:48.006 --> 31:51.419
So when I'd done, I followed her
into the-into the shop.

31:51.442 --> 31:53.149
- To chat her up?

31:53.177 --> 31:55.555
Hmm. I'd like to have seen that.

31:55.580 --> 31:58.220
Ian Paisley chatting someone up?

31:58.249 --> 32:02.425
- Oh, believe it or not, I was
quiet and shy in those days.

32:02.453 --> 32:05.662
- Dr. Paisley,
you were never quiet.

32:08.927 --> 32:10.099
- Quieter.

32:12.397 --> 32:16.004
She was up a ladder
stocking shelves.

32:18.369 --> 32:21.373
She glanced around at me,
and her cheeks went all pink.

32:21.406 --> 32:23.716
She asked me if she could
help me, and I said...

32:25.410 --> 32:28.118
"Do you have
any aeroplane biscuits?"

32:28.146 --> 32:30.183
And she said, "What are those?
I've never heard of them."

32:30.214 --> 32:34.026
And I said, "You know,
they're the wee plain ones."

32:35.086 --> 32:36.724
She started giggling.

32:43.127 --> 32:44.367
And that was that.

32:44.395 --> 32:46.636
- Ian Paisley,
the stand-up comic, huh?

32:49.534 --> 32:51.411
Tell me somethin'.

32:51.436 --> 32:54.178
After all these years,

32:54.205 --> 32:57.186
does she still enjoy
all the grandstanding?

32:57.208 --> 32:59.654
- The grand...
- Yeah, like she never says,

32:59.677 --> 33:03.215
"Ian, would you
wind your neck in?"

33:03.247 --> 33:07.696
I mean, you stood in the middle
of the European Parliament

33:07.719 --> 33:10.393
and called the Pope
the Antichrist.

33:11.689 --> 33:14.761
I mean, did she not tell you
to catch yourself on?

33:14.993 --> 33:16.438
She-she thought
that was a good idea?

33:16.461 --> 33:18.304
- She did,
and it had to be said.

33:18.329 --> 33:19.740
- You mugged the Pope.

33:19.764 --> 33:23.075
- Mr. McGuinness,
I am not a man of violence-

33:23.101 --> 33:26.742
- Do you or do you not believe

33:26.771 --> 33:30.082
that the European Union
is part of a conspiracy

33:30.108 --> 33:32.611
to create
a Roman Catholic super state

33:32.643 --> 33:33.747
controlled by the Vatican?

33:33.778 --> 33:36.088
- I do and it is.
- Brilliant.

33:36.781 --> 33:41.787
And did you or did you not
write that seat number 666

33:42.020 --> 33:46.298
in the European Parliament
is reserved for the Antichrist?

33:47.492 --> 33:49.563
Oh, fabulous.

33:49.594 --> 33:53.269
Do you really, really,
really believe all this?

33:53.297 --> 33:54.640
You know, I'm not mocking you.

33:54.665 --> 33:57.077
You're entitled
to your opinions.

33:57.769 --> 34:00.773
I'm mocking the poor blind fools
that swallow it all

34:00.805 --> 34:02.284
hook, line and sinker.

34:03.374 --> 34:06.617
They elect you
again and again and again.

34:06.644 --> 34:10.524
The most popular politician
in Europe and the most extreme.

34:10.547 --> 34:14.052
- All I do is follow
the teachings of the scriptures.

34:15.386 --> 34:18.161
And I challenge any man
to find different.

34:18.188 --> 34:19.565
- And scriptures told you

34:19.590 --> 34:21.030
to burn Catholics
out of their homes?

34:21.059 --> 34:23.596
- I didn't.
- You incited people to do it.

34:23.628 --> 34:25.232
- I preach the Lord's words.

34:25.263 --> 34:29.370
- You said priests and nuns were
handing out sub machine guns.

34:29.400 --> 34:31.710
- And they were.
- Oh, for God's sake.

34:31.735 --> 34:34.114
Do you know why,
in nearly 30 years,

34:34.138 --> 34:37.277
the IRA has never,
never once tried to kill you?

34:38.109 --> 34:40.521
Because you,
with all your bigotry,

34:40.545 --> 34:44.186
all your "Save Ulster
from Sodomy" campaigning,

34:44.215 --> 34:46.525
seein' Antichrists
around every corner,

34:46.551 --> 34:50.590
you have done more damage
to your own lot

34:50.621 --> 34:54.626
than the IRA could have ever
done with a thousand bombs.

34:54.659 --> 34:57.196
- That's a matter of opinion,
and you're wrong!

34:58.196 --> 35:01.769
Your lot have made at least
three attempts at my life.

35:01.799 --> 35:02.800
- Nope.

35:04.235 --> 35:05.805
At least our side hasn't.

35:11.109 --> 35:13.749
- <i>You can almost taste it,
can't you?</i>

35:13.778 --> 35:16.452
<i>The hatred. Thick as blood.</i>

35:17.715 --> 35:19.888
<i>It congeals in the same way too.</i>

35:20.118 --> 35:22.655
Forms a scab
that keeps the poison in.

35:22.687 --> 35:26.191
But every once in a while,
a little just leaks out.

35:26.224 --> 35:29.603
Just enough to pollute
everything it touches.

35:29.627 --> 35:32.471
Imagine the Twin Towers falling.

35:32.497 --> 35:33.703
Falling twice.

35:34.565 --> 35:37.512
That's the kind of violence
we're talking about.

35:37.535 --> 35:42.245
And all caused
by children bickering.

35:42.273 --> 35:47.552
<i>And yet these are our bright
and shining beacons of hope.</i>

35:47.578 --> 35:49.353
You see, a beating...

35:51.215 --> 35:53.695
Or a murder or a bomb

35:53.718 --> 35:56.927
<i>that kills two or three people
isn't enough anymore.</i>

35:57.155 --> 35:59.726
<i>Not since 9/11.
It means nothing.</i>

35:59.757 --> 36:03.728
For terror to be effective,
it now has to be massive.

36:05.463 --> 36:08.239
Has to be
a Hollywood spectacular.

36:08.866 --> 36:11.312
<i>And these men
haven't the stomach for it.</i>

36:11.335 --> 36:12.575
<i>Not anymore.</i>

36:13.504 --> 36:14.881
But...

36:14.906 --> 36:17.284
there's always
a new generation coming up

36:17.308 --> 36:20.346
more ambitious, more outrageous.

36:23.281 --> 36:24.419
<i>These men and these women,</i>

36:24.448 --> 36:26.928
<i>they need
to be nipped in the bud.</i>

36:29.554 --> 36:32.865
<i>And your passengers can do that</i>

36:32.890 --> 36:37.464
<i>if they can just get over
their own poisonous past.</i>

36:48.706 --> 36:50.310
How are we doing for time?

36:50.341 --> 36:52.617
- We're on schedule.
In fact, we're a little ahead.

36:52.643 --> 36:54.645
- Let's lose the security car.

37:19.637 --> 37:22.015
- Where is the security car?

37:22.240 --> 37:23.514
<i>-</i> Sir?

37:23.541 --> 37:24.952
- The security car?

37:24.976 --> 37:25.977
It was there a minute ago
and then-

37:26.010 --> 37:27.853
- To tell you the truth,
I wasn't even aware

37:27.878 --> 37:29.824
there was a security car.

37:30.581 --> 37:31.685
- Of course, there was.

37:32.984 --> 37:34.622
It was right behind us.

37:34.652 --> 37:36.723
- Oh, the irony.

37:36.754 --> 37:40.327
The great Republican
Martin McGuinness

37:40.358 --> 37:41.860
getting nervous

37:41.892 --> 37:44.964
because the Queen's men
aren't here to protect him.

37:44.996 --> 37:46.669
- It's not that. It's...

37:46.697 --> 37:48.608
- Do you think
someone's gonna take you out?

37:48.633 --> 37:52.843
This might be Scotland,
but it-it is Calvin country.

37:52.870 --> 37:54.816
There's no love lost
for the likes of you,

37:54.839 --> 37:56.409
so you might have a point.

37:57.575 --> 38:00.351
Or is it your own side
you're worried about?

38:00.378 --> 38:02.551
- Don't be ridiculous.

38:02.580 --> 38:05.959
Well, we should have protection.
We're... politicians.

38:05.983 --> 38:07.724
- Oh, really? Oh!

38:07.752 --> 38:10.392
Oh, yeah,
that's what you are, is it?

38:10.421 --> 38:12.594
Ah, well, you've come a long way

38:12.623 --> 38:14.000
from the wee guttersnipe

38:14.025 --> 38:16.528
hurling rocks
at British soldiers.

38:16.560 --> 38:20.940
Or did the, uh... the balaclava
get a bit too scratchy?

38:20.965 --> 38:24.003
Now you've a nice suit
and shiny shoes.

38:24.035 --> 38:27.676
You're quite the respectable
little democrat.

38:27.705 --> 38:29.082
- At least I aspire to it.

38:29.307 --> 38:31.378
Can I please borrow
your bloody phone?

38:31.409 --> 38:32.786
- No.

38:33.811 --> 38:36.348
- <i>You're 35 miles
from Edinburgh Airport,</i>

38:36.380 --> 38:37.916
<i>and that is not very far.</i>

38:37.948 --> 38:41.657
We've diverted you to
the Lomond Hills Regional Park

38:41.686 --> 38:44.030
to give them a bit more time.

38:44.055 --> 38:47.366
So just drive around
for as long as you can.

38:47.391 --> 38:49.598
Try not to be obvious.

38:49.627 --> 38:50.867
By the time you leave that park,

38:50.895 --> 38:53.808
we want them singing off
the same hymn sheet.

39:00.404 --> 39:01.849
- Hey, where are we goin'?

39:02.907 --> 39:04.614
- Sorry,
there's a diversion ahead.

39:04.642 --> 39:06.849
The roads flooded
with all the rain.

39:06.877 --> 39:08.618
It's just a wee bit of a detour.

39:08.646 --> 39:10.057
Shouldn't slow us down at all.

39:55.593 --> 39:57.869
- Hey, what are we doing
in the middle of a forest?

39:57.895 --> 39:59.602
<i>- Shortcut, sir.</i>

40:00.731 --> 40:03.143
<i>We'll be joining the M90
on the other side.</i>

40:03.167 --> 40:04.908
- <i>Shortcut?</i>

40:06.036 --> 40:07.481
- Shortcut?

40:15.112 --> 40:17.422
Jesus!

40:17.448 --> 40:18.483
- What's going on?

40:18.516 --> 40:20.120
- Sir, they-they appear
to have crashed.

40:20.151 --> 40:22.654
- I told you to buy time,
not bloody-

40:22.686 --> 40:24.131
<i>- Sorry. Sorry, sorry, sorry.</i>

40:24.155 --> 40:25.828
- Look, can you hear me?

40:25.856 --> 40:27.893
What the hell is going on?

40:36.634 --> 40:38.011
Are you all right, sir?

40:38.035 --> 40:39.605
Are you okay?

40:39.637 --> 40:41.639
- Yes, I am. I'm grand.

40:41.672 --> 40:43.948
Yes, uh, what was that?
- Sorry, a deer.

40:43.974 --> 40:46.750
A deer, it just ran
right out in front.

40:46.777 --> 40:48.984
I did hit the brakes,
but we slid.

40:49.013 --> 40:51.118
Are you okay?
- I'm fine.

40:51.148 --> 40:53.094
- Okay, so just stay inside

40:53.117 --> 40:55.188
while I check on the damage,

40:55.219 --> 40:57.199
and we'll be back on the road
in no time.

40:58.122 --> 40:59.931
- They're getting out.

41:01.225 --> 41:03.933
For God's sake,
don't let them get out.

41:05.496 --> 41:07.840
We need to keep <i>them in</i> the car.

41:07.865 --> 41:10.025
<i>What are they saying? I can't
hear what they're saying.</i>

41:25.683 --> 41:28.527
- There goes your party.
- No, don't even say that.

41:28.552 --> 41:31.692
Okay. This is...
This is no problem.

41:31.722 --> 41:33.793
Okay. This is no problem at all.
Now...

41:35.826 --> 41:39.273
Just, uh, I'm gonna just go
and fix the, uh...

41:39.497 --> 41:41.238
Fucking hell.

41:41.265 --> 41:42.801
<i>Just wait.</i>

41:49.006 --> 41:50.952
- About bloody time.

41:50.975 --> 41:52.852
Did you deliberately prang it?

41:52.877 --> 41:54.083
<i>- No. Okay, no.</i>

41:54.111 --> 41:56.284
What am I supposed to do now?

41:56.514 --> 41:58.187
- There was no blood or fur...

41:59.950 --> 42:02.260
On the headlight or the tire.

42:02.286 --> 42:03.993
- <i>We have</i> a <i>puncture, yes.</i>

42:04.021 --> 42:05.728
<i>I haven't changed</i> a <i>tire</i> in...

42:05.756 --> 42:07.793
I've never changed a tire.

42:07.825 --> 42:09.634
<i>We don't even know
if it's fixable.</i>

42:09.660 --> 42:11.071
- Well, first...

42:12.062 --> 42:14.099
We lose the security car.

42:14.131 --> 42:15.735
- Hmm.

42:15.766 --> 42:17.268
- Then we make
a mysterious detour

42:17.301 --> 42:19.247
that nobody else
seems to be makin'.

42:20.237 --> 42:23.309
Then we-we crash
for no obvious reason.

42:23.541 --> 42:26.715
- <i>You need to get the spare tire
out of the boot.</i>

42:26.744 --> 42:28.553
You need to get the jack,

42:28.579 --> 42:31.924
and above all, you need to hear
what they're saying.

42:31.949 --> 42:35.761
- You'd nearly think
they want us marooned out here.

42:36.720 --> 42:38.791
- You might think that.

42:38.822 --> 42:40.824
I suppose, in your line of work,

42:40.858 --> 42:44.738
you have to live with
a certain amount of paranoia.

42:44.762 --> 42:46.605
It was an accident.
It will be fixed.

42:46.630 --> 42:48.132
We will make our flight.

42:48.165 --> 42:50.076
- Yeah, you sure about that,
hmm?

42:50.100 --> 42:52.137
You get a wee Whisper
from up above, huh?

42:54.271 --> 42:57.775
Maybe he doesn't want us
to leave the talks.

42:58.676 --> 43:01.247
Maybe he thinks
your golden wedding party

43:01.278 --> 43:04.122
is an extravagance
we can't afford.

43:04.148 --> 43:05.991
- Gents,

43:06.016 --> 43:08.895
the good news is that
the engine is fine.

43:08.919 --> 43:12.162
So if you just want
to get back in the car,

43:12.189 --> 43:15.227
I'll change the tire, and we'll
soon be back on our way.

43:16.827 --> 43:19.831
- Have you ever changed
a tire before, young man?

43:20.965 --> 43:22.205
<i>-</i> Sir?

43:22.232 --> 43:24.212
- You have to jack it up, boy.

43:24.234 --> 43:26.612
That means we can't
be in the back, no!

43:31.609 --> 43:33.350
- I'm with Bertie now.

43:33.377 --> 43:35.857
Policing.
We're going round in circles.

43:38.015 --> 43:40.154
I, uh, hope you don't mind.

43:40.184 --> 43:43.028
I thought it only right
to invite Bertie to, uh...

43:43.053 --> 43:44.088
- on.

43:46.156 --> 43:48.898
- What's-what's going on?
- We had an incident.

43:48.926 --> 43:51.805
Uh, our driver
managed to crash the car.

43:51.829 --> 43:53.206
- Are they...

43:53.230 --> 43:56.700
- No, no, no. No injuries
that we're aware of.

43:57.201 --> 43:59.306
Uh, nothing too serious
with the vehicle.

43:59.336 --> 44:01.009
Uh...
- Where are they?

44:02.773 --> 44:04.252
In a forest.

44:05.709 --> 44:07.017
- What are they doing
in a forest?

44:07.044 --> 44:08.352
- Walking.

44:08.379 --> 44:11.189
- They should be near
the airport by now.

44:11.215 --> 44:12.922
- I'm afraid our grand plan
to get them talking

44:12.950 --> 44:14.861
was, uh, rather misfiring,

44:14.885 --> 44:17.058
so the situation
had to be managed.

44:17.087 --> 44:18.361
- Where's their security?

44:19.156 --> 44:20.760
- It was withdrawn.

44:22.326 --> 44:24.306
- On whose authority?

44:24.328 --> 44:27.434
- Uh, well, they needed time
and a little pressure.

44:28.432 --> 44:32.073
- So you withdrew their security

44:32.102 --> 44:35.709
and allowed a child
to crash the car.

44:36.674 --> 44:39.086
And now they're...
- Yes, Prime Minister.

44:39.109 --> 44:41.350
- Do you think
that's satisfactory?

44:42.880 --> 44:45.451
The two men upon whom this
entire peace agreement depends

44:45.683 --> 44:48.789
wandering by themselves
in a fucking wood!

44:51.789 --> 44:53.234
- And your children?

44:55.025 --> 44:58.029
What do you tell them
about the murders

44:58.062 --> 45:00.338
and the bombs and the...

45:00.364 --> 45:02.935
- You don't understand us
at all, do you?

45:03.801 --> 45:05.940
You insist on seeing it
in terms of murder...

45:05.969 --> 45:07.107
- And genocide.

45:07.137 --> 45:09.276
- Instead of people
fighting for their rights,

45:09.306 --> 45:10.785
for their country,
for their freedom-

45:10.808 --> 45:14.381
- I only judge it by
the amount of funerals I go to

45:14.411 --> 45:15.981
of ordinary, decent people.

45:16.013 --> 45:19.187
- American independence, hmm?
Terrorists?

45:19.216 --> 45:21.218
French resistance, terrorists?

45:21.251 --> 45:22.491
Horses for courses.

45:22.720 --> 45:25.200
- Do you have nothing

45:25.222 --> 45:27.133
on your conscience at all?

45:35.499 --> 45:37.445
- Sir. Sir, sir, please.

45:40.137 --> 45:41.445
- Look, I...

45:42.372 --> 45:44.352
- Tony.
- Not now.

45:44.374 --> 45:45.478
- Prime Minister.

45:48.312 --> 45:51.384
- Oh, God! Gerry!
Gerry, I can explain.

45:51.415 --> 45:53.895
- Gerry,
it was a shock to me too.

45:53.917 --> 45:56.295
But he's very good at making
something categorically wrong

45:56.320 --> 45:57.924
sound categorically right.

45:57.955 --> 45:59.161
- Bertie, that is not fair.

46:03.761 --> 46:05.001
- Where are they?

46:05.796 --> 46:07.469
- They're wandering in a forest.

46:07.498 --> 46:09.375
- But they're fine.
They're fine.

46:09.399 --> 46:10.469
Gerry, this isn't about you.

46:10.501 --> 46:12.981
It's not about Martin
or these-these images.

46:13.003 --> 46:15.313
You know that.
Bigger picture.

46:21.912 --> 46:25.223
If Bloody Sunday
hadn't happened,

46:25.249 --> 46:27.490
then we would have
just faded away.

46:28.418 --> 46:30.989
13 people
on a civil rights march

46:31.021 --> 46:33.092
shot dead by your Brits.

46:33.123 --> 46:36.366
- Oh, people in glass houses
shouldn't throw stones,

46:36.393 --> 46:38.464
as I believe you did
on that day.

46:38.495 --> 46:41.874
- Oh, piss off, you smug...

46:51.375 --> 46:54.481
13 innocent people
shot in the back, most of 'em.

46:54.511 --> 46:57.219
The next day, we'd so many
volunteers, we couldn't cope.

46:57.247 --> 46:59.523
They were-they were queuing
round the block to join us.

46:59.550 --> 47:01.552
- And you had
your license to kill.

47:01.585 --> 47:03.462
- We were fighting a civil war.

47:03.487 --> 47:04.966
- And you lost.

47:07.124 --> 47:10.003
Isn't-isn't that
what this is all about, huh?

47:11.428 --> 47:14.875
Your precious army
is so riddled with informers,

47:14.898 --> 47:17.139
you can barely
mount an operation.

47:17.167 --> 47:21.172
- I have a political mandate,
just like you.

47:21.205 --> 47:24.049
- You are nothing like me.

48:25.469 --> 48:28.177
I grew up working on farms.

48:29.273 --> 48:30.445
They're vermin.

48:31.508 --> 48:33.044
<i>-</i> It's dying-

48:33.076 --> 48:35.147
- You need to put it
out of its misery.

48:38.148 --> 48:41.220
It shouldn't be a problem
to a soldier like you.

48:57.601 --> 48:59.080
Just do it.

49:56.460 --> 49:58.371
- I'd say the car's
back that way.

50:11.508 --> 50:13.613
- And I'm telling you,
I don't see them.

50:13.643 --> 50:16.283
- Okay, okay,
about 300 meters on your right,

50:16.313 --> 50:17.724
there's a church.

50:22.052 --> 50:23.554
- I don't recognize them.

50:25.155 --> 50:27.032
They must be your lot.

50:34.331 --> 50:38.802
- Ah, these are all
illustrations from the...

50:40.137 --> 50:41.172
<i>From the Book of Martyrs.</i>

50:41.204 --> 50:43.150
- Oh, if it's not
by John Grisham,

50:43.173 --> 50:44.516
I probably haven't read it.

50:45.575 --> 50:48.215
- Back then, the common people

50:48.245 --> 50:51.055
had almost
no other reading matter

50:51.081 --> 50:54.290
except the Bible

50:54.317 --> 50:56.558
<i>and Foxe's Book of Martyrs.</i>

50:56.586 --> 51:00.500
Those who could read
could learn of the full horror

51:00.524 --> 51:04.495
of the atrocities performed
on the Protestant reformers.

51:04.528 --> 51:06.235
The illiterate

51:06.263 --> 51:08.436
could see for themselves

51:08.465 --> 51:12.106
these illustrations.

51:12.135 --> 51:15.548
The book is more
than a record of persecution.

51:15.572 --> 51:18.576
It's a living force

51:18.608 --> 51:21.418
and my inspiration.

51:22.813 --> 51:24.087
- Well...

51:25.782 --> 51:28.388
<i>We Know a thing or two
about martyrs as weâ€œ.</i>

51:29.586 --> 51:32.089
- I'm talking about
men of faith.

51:33.256 --> 51:34.394
- So am I.

51:35.592 --> 51:38.471
Ten men
starved themselves to death

51:38.495 --> 51:39.633
for what they believed in.

51:39.663 --> 51:42.234
- Murderers and bombers.

51:43.567 --> 51:47.344
- Bobby Sands was a member of
your blessed British Parliament.

51:47.370 --> 51:48.849
- He was a terrorist.

51:50.474 --> 51:53.318
- 100,000 people
attended his funeral.

51:54.344 --> 51:56.153
You think
they were all terrorists?

51:57.514 --> 51:59.357
- Your hunger strikers

51:59.382 --> 52:01.419
chose to take their own lives.

52:01.451 --> 52:05.456
That was a choice
their many victims didn't have.

52:05.489 --> 52:08.527
And you could have stopped it.

52:08.558 --> 52:11.402
- I could have?
- Yes.

52:11.428 --> 52:14.773
You, Adams...

52:14.798 --> 52:18.644
All you lot with
your ballot paper in one hand

52:18.668 --> 52:21.740
and your Armalite in the other.

52:21.771 --> 52:25.150
The government was willing
to make a deal with you,

52:25.175 --> 52:27.553
but you thought
that the publicity was worth

52:27.577 --> 52:30.786
its weight in gold,
so you wouldn't let them stop.

52:32.782 --> 52:35.422
Until one after the other,

52:35.452 --> 52:38.558
one after the other,

52:38.588 --> 52:41.262
ten men lay dead.

52:42.559 --> 52:44.505
- You know nothing about it.

52:46.196 --> 52:47.675
- I know enough.

52:47.697 --> 52:50.303
- If it wasn't for them,

52:50.333 --> 52:52.677
we wouldn't be
sittin' round a table now.

52:54.604 --> 52:57.210
- There's no deal done yet.

53:04.447 --> 53:06.620
- Bloody hell.
Whose idea was this?

53:06.650 --> 53:09.392
- It was my idea,

53:09.419 --> 53:11.399
and I take
full responsibility for it.

53:11.421 --> 53:12.866
- No, no, no, no.

53:12.889 --> 53:15.392
Well, actually, yes,

53:15.425 --> 53:17.928
but the buck stops with me.

53:19.763 --> 53:21.470
Or does it?

53:21.498 --> 53:24.411
Look, we're-we're all at it.

53:24.434 --> 53:25.970
We're in each other's
pockets on this.

53:26.203 --> 53:28.274
I mean, it goes with
the territory, doesn't it?

53:29.206 --> 53:31.914
Gerry, Martin didn't need
to make that flight.

53:31.942 --> 53:33.888
He volunteered.

53:33.910 --> 53:36.390
- The IRA Army Council ordered-
- Gerry, Gerry, come on.

53:36.413 --> 53:37.551
We know.

53:39.683 --> 53:42.220
Look, I'm on your side.

53:42.919 --> 53:44.227
Okay?

53:45.355 --> 53:47.961
Long term,
I fully support your objectives.

53:47.991 --> 53:49.971
Absolutely, a united Ireland.

53:49.993 --> 53:53.270
And, Ian Kyle Jr.,
in the short term, which,

53:53.296 --> 53:55.469
yeah, might actually
turn out to be quite long,

53:55.498 --> 53:56.738
I fully support yours too.

53:56.766 --> 53:58.473
You remain
part of the United Kingdom.

53:58.501 --> 54:01.380
I mean, my grandfather
was an Orangeman in Donegal,

54:01.404 --> 54:02.474
for goodness sake.

54:03.707 --> 54:06.347
And the moment
that you agreed to your father

54:06.376 --> 54:08.617
traveling with Martin,
you knew what this was about.

54:08.645 --> 54:10.818
So, gentlemen,

54:10.847 --> 54:12.690
I have a foot
in both graves-camps.

54:13.617 --> 54:15.460
But I favor neither.

54:15.485 --> 54:18.694
I favor... peace.

54:20.957 --> 54:24.734
Now I know
it will take a miracle

54:24.761 --> 54:26.798
for these two
to work things out.

54:27.764 --> 54:30.540
And if listening in
can make that happen,

54:30.567 --> 54:33.411
if, as a result,
we can divert traffic

54:33.436 --> 54:36.610
or switch a signal
to improve their chances,

54:36.640 --> 54:38.381
then I fully support
what Harry has done

54:38.408 --> 54:39.580
completely of his own accord.

54:41.611 --> 54:44.558
So I'm asking you, gentlemen,
who may be rightly aggrieved,

54:44.581 --> 54:46.458
to stand with me in this moment

54:46.483 --> 54:48.053
where we are perched
so precariously

54:48.285 --> 54:49.389
on the razor's edge

54:49.419 --> 54:52.832
to see this through
and walk out of this hotel

54:52.856 --> 54:54.858
and straight
into the history books.

54:54.891 --> 54:56.336
- Ditto.

54:59.562 --> 55:01.599
- Come on, big man.
We've a plane to catch.

55:09.806 --> 55:12.946
I've never been one for
talking in public, so I haven't.

55:14.010 --> 55:17.822
Well, no problem
with a small paramilitary unit.

55:19.549 --> 55:20.994
Not like you.

55:21.985 --> 55:24.795
Tens of thousands
roaring you on.

55:27.090 --> 55:28.797
It was your finest hour.

55:34.664 --> 55:36.575
Can we hear a bit of it?

55:40.704 --> 55:43.480
- I don't have the power
I used to have.

55:46.543 --> 55:48.523
I haven't been well.

55:49.779 --> 55:51.417
- Go on, you can do it.

55:51.448 --> 55:53.655
Knock it out of the park, huh?

55:54.884 --> 55:58.593
"Never, never, never!"

55:58.621 --> 56:01.830
<i>- Some say in our province!</i>

56:01.858 --> 56:05.362
<i>We say never!</i>

56:05.395 --> 56:08.968
<i>Never! Never! Never!</i>

56:08.998 --> 56:11.706
I'm not here
for your entertainment.

56:11.735 --> 56:13.646
- Then what are you here for?

56:24.614 --> 56:25.991
- I don't know.

56:26.015 --> 56:27.722
- I'll tell you why we're here

56:27.751 --> 56:29.924
in this godforsaken church.

56:30.987 --> 56:33.126
And it's nothing
you don't already know.

56:35.992 --> 56:38.700
We're here because
we are on the verge of something

56:38.728 --> 56:41.641
the wider world will applaud

56:41.664 --> 56:43.666
but our own people will hate.

56:46.569 --> 56:49.880
You are being asked
to betray your tribe.

56:50.940 --> 56:53.443
And I'm being asked
to betray mine.

56:54.744 --> 56:55.814
That's all.

57:02.819 --> 57:05.959
- How can we even contemplate

57:05.989 --> 57:07.866
doing this?

57:07.891 --> 57:09.564
Hmm?

57:15.432 --> 57:16.467
- What?

57:20.203 --> 57:23.616
- That's the first time
you've said "we."

57:30.914 --> 57:32.518
- Well.

57:32.549 --> 57:33.550
- What?

57:35.985 --> 57:39.558
You are so defensive.

57:51.134 --> 57:54.081
We've spent too much time
in graveyards.

57:54.103 --> 57:55.548
- Aye.

58:03.112 --> 58:05.524
- You know, it's not that...

58:05.548 --> 58:07.255
I don't have any regrets.
It's...

58:07.484 --> 58:09.157
- Walking on the dead there.
Use the path.

58:09.185 --> 58:10.721
Show some respect.

58:18.962 --> 58:20.737
- Do you remember Enniskillen?

58:20.763 --> 58:22.037
- Do I remember it?

58:22.065 --> 58:23.510
- No, I... I don't mean that.

58:23.533 --> 58:25.535
Of course, you remember it.
It's just-

58:25.568 --> 58:29.675
- The IRA planted a bomb
at a Remembrance Day parade,

58:29.706 --> 58:33.017
a parade to remember
Protestant and Catholic soldiers

58:33.042 --> 58:35.750
who fought on the same side
against great evil

58:35.778 --> 58:37.951
in two World Wars

58:37.981 --> 58:42.020
and murdered 11-
no, 12 innocent people.

58:42.051 --> 58:44.088
- I know what happened.

58:44.120 --> 58:45.758
But what I'm trying to say is-

58:45.788 --> 58:47.768
- Wesley and Bertha Armstrong.

58:47.790 --> 58:49.997
Kitchener and Jessie Johnston.

58:50.026 --> 58:52.666
William and Agnes Mullan.

58:52.695 --> 58:55.107
John Megaw, Georgina Quinton,

58:55.131 --> 58:58.977
Marie Wilson, Samuel Gault,
and Edward Armstrong.

58:59.002 --> 59:03.109
Ronnie Hill died after being
in a coma for 13 years.

59:03.139 --> 59:07.144
Yes, I remember Enniskillen.

59:07.176 --> 59:08.849
- Will you listen to me?

59:09.612 --> 59:11.114
It was a mistake, okay?

59:13.583 --> 59:16.086
It did irreparable damage
to our cause.

59:18.054 --> 59:19.727
When it was on the news...

59:21.724 --> 59:23.226
They were showing the video.

59:26.062 --> 59:29.600
They were showing...
Gordon Wilson talking

59:29.632 --> 59:32.943
about his... his poor daughter
under the rubble.

59:36.172 --> 59:37.742
And he was saying...

59:39.075 --> 59:40.884
That he bore us no ill will.

59:42.145 --> 59:43.317
He forgave us.

59:45.248 --> 59:49.890
My daughter...
she was only a wee tot.

59:52.622 --> 59:54.295
She came to me and asked

59:54.324 --> 59:57.965
why people
had to kill each other.

59:59.996 --> 01:00:01.304
And I said...

01:00:04.033 --> 01:00:05.876
"It's not good to kill anyone,

01:00:05.902 --> 01:00:09.782
but sometimes, if you believe
something so strongly"...

01:00:14.711 --> 01:00:16.213
And I heard myself sayin' it.

01:00:19.949 --> 01:00:23.829
And I could see in her eyes,
she was just...

01:00:23.853 --> 01:00:25.264
horrified...

01:00:27.757 --> 01:00:30.738
That I was trying to justify it.

01:00:33.930 --> 01:00:36.911
And I realized, uh...

01:00:36.933 --> 01:00:39.209
I was talking to her

01:00:39.235 --> 01:00:41.237
as a freedom fighter, not as...

01:00:42.805 --> 01:00:44.250
Not as a father.

01:00:47.710 --> 01:00:50.122
And I started to think,

01:00:50.146 --> 01:00:54.026
how would I feel

01:00:54.050 --> 01:00:55.859
if she was under that rubble?

01:00:59.155 --> 01:01:03.103
If she was the one I had to hold

01:01:03.126 --> 01:01:05.766
while her life ebbed away?

01:01:05.795 --> 01:01:06.933
- Martin.

01:01:08.097 --> 01:01:11.738
- And that's when
I finally understood...

01:01:13.169 --> 01:01:16.241
That things had to change.

01:01:16.272 --> 01:01:19.185
We...
that the killing had to stop.

